MNHR is already available in DASH up to 2019 and so the only variables needed that are not in DASH are:

2. Longitude and latitude of cluster in which participant was seen.

ASPIRIN is already available in DASH and so the only variables needed that are not in DASH are:

‌

Additionally, there is overlap between participants enrolled in MNHR and ASPIRIN. To avoid counting the same participant twice (once in MNH, once in ASPIRIN), we will also provide the MNHR participant ID for participants enrolled in ASPIRIN. However, not all participants in ASPIRIN are included in MNHR.

‌

Additionally, note that since MNHR was used to capture some of the data needed for the ASPIRIN trial, MNHR data was locked at the time ASPIRIN was over for analyses to be conducted for ASPIRIN. However, MNHR data continued to be updated later for participants included in the ASPIRIN analyses and so the most up to date information for ASPIRIN participants would likely come from the DASH release for MNHR, rather than the DASH release for ASPIRIN.

Dear Alison,

Moving forward, we will request the study documents, and I will review everything to ensure eligibility. You will be engaged throughout the entire process. Should the study not meet eligibility criteria for any reason, we will clarify those reasons with you.

INTERBIO-21st has two components: the Fetal and Neonatal Studies. In the Fetal Study, which is limited to certain settings, women are being monitored from early pregnancy onwards so as to capture very detailed information about fetal growth patterns; in the Neonatal Study, women are identified at birth provided that gestational age has been confirmed by ultrasound < 24 weeks’ gestation.
